<taxonomicName authority="Duges, 1894" authorityName="Duges" authorityYear="1894" box="[151,606,1776,1802]" class="Reptilia" family="Amphisbaenidae" genus="Hemichirotes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tridactylus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,448,1776,1802]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="39">Hemichirotes tridactylus</emphasis>
Dugès, 
<number box="[546,606,1776,1802]" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" value="1894.0">1894</number>
</taxonomicName>
a
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1847,2016]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1436,151,429]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="40" pageId="6" pageNumber="39">
The original description of this species appeared in Cope (
<number box="[818,876,1847,1872]" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" value="1894.0">1894</number>
) in the May issue of “The American Naturalist”. Cope credited the description to Dugès’ manuscript describing a new amphisbaenian from Guerrero, 
<collectingCountry box="[1278,1367,1883,1908]" name="Mexico" pageId="6" pageNumber="39">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. Cope published an abbreviated version of the description that Dugès published in “La Naturaleza” (Dugès 
<number box="[1350,1409,1919,1944]" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" value="1894.0">1894</number>
b). Copes’paper reproduces five of the eight figures as they were published by Dugès (Pl. XX 
<number box="[1181,1196,1955,1979]" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" value="1.0">1</number>
’ and 
<number box="[1260,1304,1955,1980]" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" value="4.0" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="1.0">1–7</number>
). To satisfy the criterion of availability, according to Article 5.1. 
<number box="[747,757,1991,2015]" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" value="1.0">1</number>
of the ICZN (
<number box="[921,980,1991,2016]" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" value="1999.0">1999</number>
), the name should be credited to Dugès, since Cope had no specimen, at ANSP or USNM, upon which to base his description (Cochran 
<number box="[1271,1330,152,176]" pageId="7" pageNumber="40" value="1961.0">1961</number>
; Malnate 
<number box="[151,209,188,213]" pageId="7" pageNumber="40" value="1971.0">1971</number>
), the figures reproduced in Cope (
<number box="[593,651,188,213]" pageId="7" pageNumber="40" value="1894.0">1894</number>
) are the same as those made by Dugès except for a drawing of a scale (
<figureCitation box="[159,254,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 6. A" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1321,1342]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,365,1299]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,365,1299]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. A, Holotype of Tapaya orbicularis longicaudatus (HE 422); B, Holotype of Eumeces altamirani (HE 397); C, Holotype of Eumeces rovirosae (HE 189); D, Holotype of Erythrolamprus grammophrys (HE 112)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/269216/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="40">
Figure 
<quantity box="[241,254,224,248]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="6.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="40" unit="g" value="6.0">6</quantity>
</figureCitation>
g in Cope 
<number box="[371,428,223,248]" pageId="7" pageNumber="40" value="1894.0">1894</number>
) and published later the same year. When Smith &amp; Taylor (
<number box="[1098,1157,223,248]" pageId="7" pageNumber="40" value="1950.0">1950</number>
), published the checklist of Mexican reptiles; they reported that the only specimen known at the time, was the 
<typeStatus box="[1098,1146,261,284]" pageId="7" pageNumber="40">type</typeStatus>
at the MADUG (Smith &amp; Taylor 
<number box="[230,292,295,320]" pageId="7" pageNumber="40" value="1950.0">1950</number>
: 
<number box="[296,326,295,320]" pageId="7" pageNumber="40" value="38.0">38</number>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,429]" pageId="7" pageNumber="40">
The 
<typeStatus box="[249,347,332,357]" pageId="7" pageNumber="40">holotype</typeStatus>
for this species is still at the MADUG (HE 
<number box="[836,881,332,356]" pageId="7" pageNumber="40" value="127.0">127</number>
; 
<figureCitation box="[893,958,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 5. A" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1510,1531]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,554,1487]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,554,1488]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 5. A, Jar containing three syntypes of Hemitriton asper (HE 1219 – 1221); B, Holotype of Hemichirotes tridactylus (HE 127); C, Syntype of Hemidactylus navarri, adult (HE 647); D, Syntype of Hemidactylus navarri, juvenile (HE 1222)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/269215/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="40">
Fig. 
<number box="[944,958,332,357]" pageId="7" pageNumber="40" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
B). A detailed description of this specimen is given by Smith &amp; Necker (
<number box="[480,540,367,392]" pageId="7" pageNumber="40" value="1943.0">1943</number>
).
</paragraph>
